# GitHub-Driven Self-Healing Flow

This document describes how router logs flowing into GitHub drive the
human-in-the-loop self-healing pipeline.

## End-to-end pipeline

```
GNS3 Router
   │  (syslog UDP/514)
   ▼
Local syslog server  (gns3-router-logs/syslog_server.py)
   │  git add / commit / push on every interface/config event
   ▼
GitHub repo  ajaysartaj-gif/gns3-router-logs  →  network_audit.log
   │  raw.githubusercontent.com (HTTP read, no SSH needed)
   ▼
GitHubLogEngine        (core/github_log_engine.py)   ← NEW
   │  parses Cisco syslog → anomaly dicts, tracks interface state
   ▼
AutonomousMonitor      (core/autonomous_monitor.py)
   │  Phase 1: telemetry → detect → AI RCA → remediation plan
   ▼
APPROVAL GATE          (Streamlit "Workflows" page)  ← human in the loop
   │  operator clicks ✅ APPROVE FIX  /  ❌ REJECT
   ▼
Phase 2: NetworkFixer  (core/network_fixer.py)
   │  SSH/Telnet into the router (admin/admin by default)
   │  interface_down → `interface X` / `no shutdown` / verify
   ▼
Verification + incident closure
```

## Why read from GitHub instead of SSH?

A cloud-hosted Streamlit app cannot reach the GNS3 lab over SSH. Routing logs
through GitHub means the platform only needs an outbound HTTPS read to detect
problems. The actual *fix* still requires SSH reachability to the router (via a
pingpy/ngrok tunnel configured in **Admin → Connection**); detection and fixing
are deliberately decoupled.

## What the engine detects

It reconstructs current interface state by replaying every log line in order, so
an interface that went **down** and later came back **up** is *not* reported.
Only interfaces whose latest observed state is `down` or `administratively down`
become actionable `interface_down` anomalies, which the `NetworkFixer` already
knows how to remediate with `no shutdown`.

`%SYS-5-CONFIG_I` (config-change) lines are parsed and shown in the feed but are
informational, not actionable.

## Configuration

Set these as environment variables or Streamlit secrets:

```toml
GNS3_LOG_GITHUB_URL = "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ajaysartaj-gif/gns3-router-logs/main/network_audit.log"
GNS3_LOG_DEFAULT_DEVICE = "R1"          # used for log lines with no hostname token
# GNS3_LOG_GITHUB_TOKEN = "ghp_..."     # only needed if the log repo is PRIVATE

# Required for the FIX step to reach the router:
GNS3_ROUTER_HOST = "your-tunnel-host"
GNS3_ROUTER_PORT = "37459"
GNS3_SSH_USER = "admin"
GNS3_SSH_PASS = "admin"
```

The log source can also be configured at runtime in **Admin → Connection →
GitHub Log Source**, which includes a live feed and a "Poll Now" button.

## Operating it

1. Open the **Admin → Connection** tab, confirm the GitHub Log Source shows
   parsed lines.
2. Set the **Router SSH Host/Port** so Phase 2 can reach the router.
3. Start monitoring (the dashboard auto-polls). When an interface is down, a
   card appears on the **Workflows** page: AI root-cause + the exact CLI plan.
4. Click **✅ APPROVE FIX**. On the next cycle the platform SSHes in, runs
   `no shutdown`, verifies, and closes the incident. **❌ REJECT** clears it.

> Note: `admin/admin` is the GNS3 lab default. For anything beyond a lab,
> move credentials into Streamlit secrets and use per-device credentials.
